@popaganda. Very much here for this #console-content. I have two approaches for console mixing:
A) Keep it on the console. Usually means keeping it on the board for a few days while people chime in with their input. Usually the band will be on board with this workflow and understand that part of the magic of this workflow is to commit to things and make decisions quickly. I was working on a console with automation, so that was useful for fine-tuning a mix by modern standards… but not impossible with static faders.
B) Have enough I/O and set each console channel as an insert in Pro Tools. This was the hybrid workflow that really worked for me. It was also the gateway to integrating outboard gear. When something needed the console treatment, I’d add the insert, get it vibing in the mix, and then once I was ready to print a pass, I’d commit all the inserts in real time. The session was getting summed in the box and everything came up perfectly for recalls. This was a great way of getting the sound and workflow but staying sane in the modern record making world.

@masteredbyjack
I have a similar workflow with Asana, where I track work in progress, scheduled tasks, to be scheduled, to be checked and delivered, and completed projects. It’s a lifesaver, especially when managing multiple projects. I use Notion for personal projects, so I can relate to using these types of tools. Thanks for recommending texts.com—I’ll check it out!

For revisions, I try to get to them as soon as possible, but during super busy weeks, it can take a couple of days to fit them in, especially for mixes where revisions may take longer.

@Josh Bowman
I’m lucky to have a great assistant who prepares sessions, organizes files into my template, quality checks the files we receive and handles back-and-forth communication with clients for the files. This frees me up to just focus on mixing. She also prepares deliverables like stems and instrumental exports and recently started helping with troubleshooting tasks, which i must say, is the best thing ever hahah

I also now only schedule the mix once the session is fully prepped. I used to schedule in advance, but files often arrived late, so this has made a big difference in managing my time.

@oaklandmatt Great episode yesterday! 

You did leave me a little curious tho! You said, you were handing in your first ableton mix. (I hope you did a short square wave blip at the beginning and end or @BatMeckley might come after you and your not sample accurate multitracks 😅)

You said you got your vocal mix in protools and then pulled it into ableton, for practical reasons. Does that mean you bounced the wet vocal and just had a vocal track, and mixed the beat around that or did you bounce the dry vocal and recreate your chain from protools, so you’d still be able to tweak it in ableton? Curious about this workflow, because I like yourself also always produce in ableton, and record people outside of ableton.

This is something I’m still figuring out. I went through phases of not enough bass, too much bass, and now trying to find a balance. 

@Maxim mentioned how Manny’s Kendrick mixes don’t have too much going on at 40hz (I think this is the case on many of his mixes), but his basses or kicks sound HUGE. Not having too much lows and great balancing is probably what allows his mixes to have the loudness he does. 

While Jon’s philosophy is to save and cherish the low low subs, when you look at the meter, they’re not hitting like crazy amount. But I still feel that low low, which I also love.

if you happen to have a MWTM subscription Eddie Kramer discusses exactly this as being the necessary process when they had to commit everything to 4 tracks (i think) forJimi Hendrix-  are you experienced . Its an inspiring listen to hear what they achoeved that way..
i know you mention the pie comp a lot, kramer Loves that comp lol, he talks about smashing the pianos and guitars with it.

@cian riordan coincidentally i was just watching st,Vincent’s production process video on reverb over the last few days and wondered how much of what she does ....with the verbs and delays comes baked in to you ...and if so how you approached it as a mixer. I wondered if it sort of tied your hands a bit for possible decisions...but from your post above about baking it in early  ....i guess it suits just fine. V Dope
